The Second R: Resonance — Are Your Messages Landing?
What Is Resonance in ABM?
Reaching the right people is only half the battle. The second R, Resonance, measures whether your content and messaging are actually connecting with your target accounts. Are they engaging? Are they responding? Are they moving forward?

Resonance is where many manufacturers struggle because it requires a level of content personalization and relevance that goes beyond standard campaign metrics. A click is not enough. You need to know whether the right person at the right account is engaging with the right content at the right time.

Key Metrics to Track for Resonance
Engagement Rate by Account: Track how individual accounts are engaging with your campaigns, emails, and content assets. A spike in engagement from a target account is a strong buying signal. Look for patterns: multiple people from the same account consuming similar content is a sign that an internal conversation may be happening.

Content Consumption Depth: Are prospects skimming a blog post, or are they downloading a whitepaper, watching a full product demo video, and returning to your website multiple times? Depth of engagement is far more predictive of buying intent than surface-level clicks.

Email Response and Reply Rates: In manufacturing ABM, personalized email sequences remain one of the highest-performing tactics. Track not just open rates but reply rates, which indicate that your messaging resonated enough to prompt a response.

Event and Webinar Participation: Are contacts from your target accounts attending your virtual events, product demos, or industry webinars? Event participation is a high-intent signal that deserves its own tracking category.

Social Engagement: Are decision-makers at target accounts engaging with your LinkedIn content, commenting on posts, or sharing your thought leadership articles? Social resonance is often an early signal of deeper interest.

How to Improve and Measure Resonance
The key to strong Resonance is hyper-personalized content. Manufacturers should develop content that speaks directly to the pain points of specific industries, roles, and buying stages. A procurement director at an automotive manufacturer has very different concerns than an operations manager at a food processing company.

Use dynamic content tools and personalization platforms to tailor landing pages, email sequences, and ad creative to individual accounts. Then track engagement at the account level, not just the campaign level, to understand which messages are truly resonating.

